Note: ========================================
Note: x86-64 Assembly Emitter
Note: ========================================
Note: Buffered x86-64 assembly output. Buffer management is delegated to
Note: the shared byte-buffer foundation in emitter_common.runa. x86-specific
Note: helpers (emit_integer, emit_comment using '#', emit_tab) are retained
Note: as thin wrappers over the shared primitives.
Note: ========================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/emitter_common.runa" as EmitterCommon
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as MemoryCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

@Reasoning:
Typed handle for the x86-64 GNU assembler (gas) backend; distinct type
keeps the dispatch table in hir_to_x86.runa unambiguous.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three fields shadow the raw EmitterCommon byte buffer.
@End Implementation

Type called "X86Emitter":
    buffer as Integer
    capacity as Integer
    length as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Factory entry hiding EmitterCommon from hir_to_x86.runa.
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_x86_emitter" returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_create from EmitterCommon
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lifecycle pair for create_x86_emitter.
@End Reasoning

@Security_Scope:
Caller must guarantee the handle is live and not already destroyed.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "destroy_x86_emitter" takes emitter as Integer:
    proc emitter_raw_destroy from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process

@Reasoning:
Pre-sizing hook for large compilation units (e.g., the whole compiler).
@End Reasoning

Process called "ensure_capacity" takes emitter as Integer, additional_bytes as Integer:
    proc emitter_raw_ensure_capacity from EmitterCommon with emitter, additional_bytes
End Process

@Reasoning:
Thin wrapper that flips the argument order of MemoryCore.memory_copy so
call sites can read source-then-dest left-to-right; used when copying
constant data into the .data section buffer.
@End Reasoning

@Security_Scope:
Caller is responsible for source/dest validity and the non-overlap
assumptions of memory_copy.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "copy_memory" takes source as Integer, dest as Integer, size as Integer:
    proc memory_copy from MemoryCore with dest, source, size
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single-byte primitive for x86 punctuation (commas, parentheses, percent
sign for registers, dollar sign for immediates).
@End Reasoning

@Performance_Hints:
Hot path. O(1) amortized.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "emit_char" takes emitter as Integer, char as Integer:
    proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bulk emission for x86 mnemonics (movq, addq, callq, ret) and register
names (%rax, %rbx, etc.).
@End Reasoning

@Performance_Hints:
Hot path. O(n) in input length.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "emit_string" takes emitter as Integer, string as Integer:
    proc emitter_raw_emit_string from EmitterCommon with emitter, string
End Process

@Reasoning:
x86 immediate operands and address displacements are written as decimal
integers (or as $0x... for hex); this helper covers the decimal form,
which dominates non-mask immediates.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
For negatives, emits '-' (45) and negates the value. Zero emits '0'
(48). Otherwise generates digits by repeated modulo-10 into a 32-byte
scratch buffer, then walks the scratch in reverse to emit them
most-significant-first. Frees the scratch before return.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(log10(value)) bytes with one allocation/deallocation cycle. Scratch
buffer is sized for any 64-bit integer.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "emit_integer" takes emitter as Integer, value as Integer:
    Note: Emit an integer as decimal string. Handles negatives and zero.
    If value is less than 0:
        proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 45
        Set value to -value
    End If

    If value is equal to 0:
        proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 48
        Return
    End If

    Let digits be proc allocate from Layout with 32
    Let digit_count be 0

    While value is greater than 0:
        Let digit be value modulo by 10
        proc memory_set_byte from MemoryCore with digits, digit_count, 48 plus digit
        Set digit_count to digit_count plus 1
        Set value to value divided by 10
    End While

    Let i be digit_count minus 1
    While i is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let digit_char be proc memory_get_byte from MemoryCore with digits, i
        proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, digit_char
        Set i to i minus 1
    End While

    proc deallocate from Layout with digits
End Process

@Reasoning:
Standalone newline used to terminate each x86 instruction or directive.
@End Reasoning

Process called "emit_newline" takes emitter as Integer:
    proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 10
End Process

@Reasoning:
x86 assembly is conventionally indented 4 spaces for instructions inside
functions; labels remain flush left. This helper handles the instruction
indent.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Multiplies the indent level by 4 and emits that many ASCII SPACE bytes.
Uses spaces (not tabs) for consistent column alignment across editors.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_indent" takes emitter as Integer, level as Integer:
    Note: 4-space indentation per x86 assembly readability convention.
    Let total_spaces be level multiplied by 4
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than total_spaces:
        proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 32
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Some legacy/external assembly snippets prefer tab indentation; emit_tab
exists for compatibility when reproducing such conventions.
@End Reasoning

Process called "emit_tab" takes emitter as Integer:
    proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 9
End Process

@Reasoning:
GNU as (the GNU assembler) uses '#' as the line-comment introducer on
x86; this helper emits a properly-formed comment line so call sites
don't have to remember the convention or the trailing newline.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits '#' (35), then ' ' (32) for readability, then the comment text,
then a terminating LF (10).
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_comment" takes emitter as Integer, comment_text as Integer:
    Note: Emit x86 GNU-as comment using "# " prefix and a trailing newline.
    proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 35
    proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 32
    proc emitter_raw_emit_string from EmitterCommon with emitter, comment_text
    proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 10
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the accumulated x86 assembly for the driver to hand to gas.
@End Reasoning

@Security_Scope:
Returned pointer aliases the emitter's internal buffer; do not free
directly and do not use after destroy_x86_emitter.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_output" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_get_output from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process

@Reasoning:
Named "get_position" because assembly toolchains historically refer to
the buffer offset as position; exposes byte count for diff tools.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_position" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_length from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lets the driver reuse a single emitter across multiple x86 source files.
@End Reasoning

Process called "reset" takes emitter as Integer:
    proc emitter_raw_reset from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process
